rovide high resolution aerial images and videos almost immediately with a fraction of cost of satellite images oraerial images from planes. UAVshas beenused in manyapplications, suchasnatural resource monitoring, media, survey, etc. They can also be used to determine object dimensions, such as building or tree height by processing images with photogrammetry software. The objective of this study was to estimate the crown height of Yangna (Dipterocarpus alatus Roxb.) using aerial images captured from small UAV (DJI phantom 4). The UAV, with 12 megapixel stock camera, flew over Yangna plantationsat altitudeof90 meter. Aerial images weretaken with80 percentoverlap (bothacrossand along track), which werethenused tocreate3Dmodel, DigitalTerrain Model (DTM)and DigitalSurface Model (DSM)usinga photogrammetry software - Agisoft Photoscan. The study areas were Yangna plantations found in Land Development Regional Office 5 -Khonkaen(Site1)and KhonKaen University(Site2). Images takenfrom both plantationsites wereused tocreateorthophoto with resolution of 0.035 and 0.037 meter respectively. DSM and DTM were created with resolution of 0.071 and 0.074 meter from plantation site 1 and site 2 respectively. From the 3D model results, each Yangna crown displayed a conical shape. The number of Yangna trees could be visually counted from the orthophotos, which tallied at 684 and 387 in site 1 and site 2 respectively. Random trees were selected at both sites for height measuring to assess DSM accuracy. In site 1, totalof247Yangna trees’height were measured, whichvaried from 7to25 meter withtheaverageheightof16.9 meter. Insite2, theaverageheight was7.3 meter and varied between2and 19 meter from 179trees measured. Whencompared with height calculated from DSM and DTM, site 1 had the average height of 17.4 meter varying from 6.3 to 25.7 meter, while site 2 has average height of 8.14 meter, varying from 1.5 to 18.2 meter. The average height differences between measured heights and models’ heights were 0.38 and 0.34 meter for site 1 and site 2 respectively. The accuracy of estimations was assessed through basic statistics, such as Mean Absolute Error (MAE) were 2.08 and 1.30 for site 1 and site 2 respectively. and Root mean square error (RMSE) were 2.74 and 1.73 for site 1 and site 2 respectively. This disparity could have arisen from the low canopy density which could cause error in the DSM value. ','Journal','Article','Journal of Remote Sensing and GIS Association of Thailand','[{\"$\": \"DTM\"}, {\"$\": \"DSM\"}, {\"$\": \"UAV\"}, {\"$\": \"Dipterocarpus alatus Roxb.\"}]','https://tci-thailand.org/wp-content/themes/magazine-style/tci_search/article.html?b3BlbkFydGljbGUmaWQ9MzEzNjMz',NULL,2018,'19','พิเศษ',0,'103-118',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(549,'Android Application for Tourism Support System in Phan Don and Pakho National Forest, Udon Thani Province','','Journal','Article','Journal of Remote Sensing and GIS Association of Thailand','[{\"$\": \"\"}]','https://tci-thailand.org/wp-content/themes/magazine-style/tci_search/article.html?b3BlbkFydGljbGUmaWQ9MTk4MTQz',NULL,2016,'17','พิเศษ',0,'168-179',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(550,'LateriticSoil Mapping in Khon Kaen Province Using Landsat 8 Satellite Image','','Journal','Article','Journal of Remote Sensing and GIS Association of Thailand','[{\"$\": \"\"}]','https://tci-thailand.org/wp-content/themes/magazine-style/tci_search/article.html?b3BlbkFydGljbGUmaWQ9MTk4MTQ2',NULL,2016,'17','พิเศษ',0,'203-212',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(551,'Database to Ontology Mapping System','This paper presents the development of Database-to-Ontology Mapping tools. The purpose of this system is to extend the tools capabilities that developed by NECTEC in order to support variety ontology development tools and variety DBMS. The development approach is based on matching method. In order to evaluate the capability of the proposed system, we use data from the Jerry?s research to evaluate the system comparing to the NectecD2OMAP. 